\i\fs71\fsmilli35712 \cf2 \cb3 How it relates to investing
\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs55\fsmilli27648 \cf2 \cb3 The key to understanding and creating lollapalooza effects is being able to understand how various models relate to one another. Once these relationships are understood, the next step is to build an understanding of what effect the combination will have on a given situation. For example, Ansys, a technology firm creating software that simulates product performance in a virtual environment, has been experiencing a lollapalooza effect caused by the decreased cost of computing power and the increasing acceptance of the cost benefits its technology provides to its customers.\cb1 \
\cb3 In investing, the biggest lollapalooza effect occurs when you find a high-quality company selling for below your estimate of its intrinsic value, and led by a management team that understands capital allocation. Henry Singleton of Teledyne is a good example. Between 1961 and 1969 he made 130 acquisitions at attractive prices. After that period, however, acquisitions became less appealing, and his company\'92s stock price declined. He then switched course, tendering eight offers from 1972 to 1984 to repurchase shares in his company. This allowed him to buy back 90% of his stock! Singleton\'92s capital allocation strategy\'97purchasing undervalued companies, then buying back his own undervalued stock\'97created a nearly ninefold outperformance of other conglomerates during that period and more than a twelvefold outperformance of the S&P 500.
